In modern web browsers, you can use the `html2canvas` library to take a screenshot of a web page or a specific element on the page. Since taking a screenshot of a page is not natively supported by plain JavaScript without the use of external libraries or browser-specific extensions, here is a functional example using `html2canvas`.

First, you need to include the `html2canvas` library in your page. You can add it via a CDN like so:

```html
<script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/html2canvas/1.4.1/html2canvas.min.js"></script>
```

Then you can create a function to take a screenshot of the entire page or a specific element:

```javascript
function takeScreenshot(element = document.body) {
    html2canvas(element).then(function(canvas) {
        // Create a base64 image URL
        var imageURL = canvas.toDataURL("image/png");

        // Below are examples of what you can do with the screenshot

        // 1. Display the screenshot on the same page
        /*
        var imgElement = document.createElement('img');
        imgElement.src = imageURL;
        document.body.appendChild(imgElement);
        */

        // 2. Download the screenshot as a PNG
        /*
        var a = document.createElement('a');
        a.href = imageURL;
        a.download = 'screenshot.png';
        a.click();
        */

    }).catch(function(error) {
        console.error('Screenshot failed', error);
    });
}
```

To use this function, just call `takeScreenshot()` for capturing the entire body of the page, or pass a specific DOM element to it, like `takeScreenshot(document.getElementById('specific-element'))`.

Make sure you have the appropriate CORS permissions if you are trying to capture an iframe or an element with content loaded from another origin.

Always be aware of privacy and legal requirements when taking screenshots of web pages, particularly with content that is not your own.

If you need to dynamically load the `html2canvas` library and use it within your JavaScript, you can create a function that injects the script tag into your HTML document and then executes the screenshot function once the library is loaded. Here's a complete example of how to do this:

```javascript
function loadHtml2Canvas(callback) {
    // Check if html2canvas is already loaded
    if (window.html2canvas) {
        callback();
        return;
    }

    // Create script element
    var script = document.createElement('script');
    script.onload = function () {
        // Once the script is loaded, execute the callback
        callback();
    };
    script.src = 'https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/html2canvas/1.4.1/html2canvas.min.js';

    // Append the script to the document head
    document.head.appendChild(script);
}

function takeScreenshot(element = document.body) {
    if (window.html2canvas) {
        // If html2canvas is available, use it
        window.html2canvas(element).then(function (canvas) {
            // Operations with the canvas go here
            // Example: Append the canvas to the body of the document
            document.body.appendChild(canvas);
        });
    } else {
        console.error('html2canvas is not loaded yet.');
    }
}

// Example usage of the functions:

// Load the html2canvas library and then take a screenshot of the whole page
loadHtml2Canvas(() => takeScreenshot());

// Load the html2canvas library and then take a screenshot of a specific element
loadHtml2Canvas(() => takeScreenshot(document.getElementById('specific-element')));
```

This example defines two functions: `loadHtml2Canvas` and `takeScreenshot`. The `loadHtml2Canvas` function checks if `html2canvas` is already available. If not, it creates a script tag, sets the source to the `html2canvas` CDN, and appends it to the document's head. When the script finishes loading, the provided callback is executed.

The code uses `document.body.appendChild(canvas)` for demonstration purposes, which merely appends the screenshot canvas to the body of the document after the screenshot is taken. You may replace this with your own logic, such as presenting the image or initiating a download.

Remember that when using dynamically injected scripts, it is generally better to manage possible error cases such as failing to load the external script. This can be done by listening for the `script.onerror` event and handling it appropriately.

To output the screenshot as a PNG image, you can modify the `takeScreenshot` function to convert the canvas to a data URL and then create a mechanism to download the image as a PNG file. Here is the updated code with the respective changes for outputting the screenshot as a PNG:

```javascript
function loadHtml2Canvas(callback) {
    // Check if html2canvas is already loaded
    if (window.html2canvas) {
        callback();
        return;
    }

    // Create script element
    var script = document.createElement('script');
    script.onload = function () {
        // Once the script is loaded, execute the callback
        callback();
    };
    script.onerror = function () {
        console.error('Failed to load html2canvas library.');
    };
    script.src = 'https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/html2canvas/1.4.1/html2canvas.min.js';

    // Append the script to the document head
    document.head.appendChild(script);
}

function takeScreenshot(element = document.body) {
    if (window.html2canvas) {
        // If html2canvas is available, use it
        window.html2canvas(element).then(function (canvas) {
            // Convert the canvas to a data URL (PNG by default)
            var imageURL = canvas.toDataURL("image/png");

            // Create a link element for downloading
            var downloadLink = document.createElement('a');
            downloadLink.href = imageURL;
            downloadLink.download = 'screenshot.png';

            // Append the link to the body and trigger the download
            document.body.appendChild(downloadLink);
            downloadLink.click();

            // Clean up by removing the link
            document.body.removeChild(downloadLink);
        });
    } else {
        console.error('html2canvas is not loaded yet.');
    }
}

// Example usage of the functions:

// Load the html2canvas library and then take a screenshot of the whole page
loadHtml2Canvas(() => takeScreenshot());

// Load the html2canvas library and then take a screenshot of a specific element
// loadHtml2Canvas(() => takeScreenshot(document.getElementById('specific-element')));
```

This script defines a function `loadHtml2Canvas` that injects the html2canvas library into the page. Once the script is loaded, it invokes a callback function to take the screenshot. The `takeScreenshot` function then uses `html2canvas` to capture the content of the specified element as a canvas. It converts the canvas to a data URL with PNG format, and creates an anchor (`<a>`) element to facilitate the PNG image download with the filename `screenshot.png`. It appends the anchor element to the document, triggers the download by simulating a click, and then removes the anchor element from the document body after the download has been initiated.

Please note that in some browsers, the automatic download may be blocked due to security settings or user preferences. Users may need to allow downloads or adjust settings to enable this feature for your site.

