Below is a revised version of the function that addresses these issues:

```javascript
let post = args.post;

function convertToHTML(text) {
  const lines = text.split('\n');
  const htmlLines = lines.map(line => {
    // Handle headings that start with '#'
    if (line.startsWith('#')) {
      const level = line.indexOf(' ') - 1; // Correcting level to be the number of '#' characters
      const headingText = line.slice(level + 2).trim(); // Skip past the '#' characters and the following space
      return `<h${level}>${headingText}</h${level}>`;
    }
    // Handle non-empty lines by wrapping them in <p> tags
    else if (line.trim() !== '') {
      return `<p>${line.trim()}</p>`; // Trimming to ensure we don't create empty paragraphs from lines with whitespace
    }
    // Exclude empty lines, do not wrap them in <p> tags
    return '';
  });

  // Join the non-empty HTML lines with newline character
  const htmlText = htmlLines.filter(line => line !== '').join('\n');

  return htmlText;
}

const htmlResult = convertToHTML(post);
console.log(htmlResult);

let postList = args.postList || [];
postList.push(htmlResult);

return postList;
```

Here are the changes made and some explanations:

1. Removed the unnecessary `.forEach` loop since we can filter out empty elements within the `.map` method itself.
2. Corrected `level` calculation to determine the heading size based on the number of '#' characters.
3. Changed logic in `.map` to directly return an empty string for lines that only contain whitespace instead of `<p></p>` or `<p>\n</p>`.
4. Used the `.filter` method to exclude empty strings from the final `htmlLines` array.
5. Replaced the check for `'<p></p>'` with a trim check to handle lines with only whitespace.
6. In the original code, the condition `line.trim() !== '<p></p>'` was likely intended to detect non-empty paragraphs, but this will not work as intended because it would only exclude lines that are exactly `'<p></p>'`. Instead, we check for any non-empty line and wrap it in `<p>` tags.

Remember to pass the `args` object with a `post` property containing the text you want to convert to HTML, as well as an optional `postList` array for accumulating results. This example assumes the structure of `args` and behavior of the `convertToHTML` function based on the provided context.
